                            Content = @"
                                <blockquote><p><span style=""color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial; display: inline !important; float: none;"" data-pasted=""true"">&ldquo;Words are really beautiful, but they&rsquo;re limited. Words are very male, very structured. But the voice is the netherworld, the darkness, where there&rsquo;s nothing to hang onto. The voice comes from a part of you that just knows and expresses and is. I need to inhabit every bit of lyric, or else I can&rsquo;t bring the song to you &ndash; or else it&rsquo;s just words.&rdquo;</span></p></blockquote><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<img src=""https://res.cloudinary.com/dc1pocu3o/image/upload/v1762615476/jeff.jpg"" style=""width: 300px;"" class=""fr-fic fr-dii"">&nbsp;<img src=""https://res.cloudinary.com/dc1pocu3o/image/upload/v1762615604/jeff5.jpg"" style=""width: 300px;"" class=""fr-fic fr-dii""></p><p><br></p><p style=""box-sizing: border-box; margin-block: 24px 0px; max-width: 1248px; margin-left: auto !important; margin-right: auto !important; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.56; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 24px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;"" data-pasted=""true"">That quote comes from Jeff Buckley in a 1994 edition of&nbsp;<em style=""box-sizing: border-box;"">Interview&nbsp;</em>magazine. That same year, Buckley released his brilliant debut studio album&nbsp;<a href=""https://open.spotify.com/album/7yQtjAjhtNi76KRu05XWFS?si=l2javf2-ThWpMdrBUiIsKw"" target=""_blank"" rel=""noopener noreferrer"" style=""box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(212, 79, 73); text-decoration: none; transition: 0.2s ease-in-out;""><em style=""box-sizing: border-box;"">Grace</em></a>, which, sadly, comprises a large portion of his musical legacy as a result of his death at the age of 30 in 1997. It&rsquo;s also a quote that plays into the misconception, given momentum since his death by the popularity of his famously ethereal version of Leonard Cohen&rsquo;s &ldquo;Hallelujah,&rdquo; that Buckley was an interpreter first and foremost.</p><p style=""box-sizing: border-box; margin-block: 24px 0px; max-width: 1248px; margin-left: auto !important; margin-right: auto !important; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.56; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 24px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;"">He was somewhat underwhelmed by his own songwriting skills, yet there is evidence on <em style=""box-sizing: border-box;"">Grace</em>, particularly on the transcendently anguished &ldquo;Lover, You Should&rsquo;ve Come Over,&rdquo; that Buckley was as adept at crafting words and melodies as he was at performing them. Even with a hint of grunge in the guitars, &ldquo;Lover&rdquo; is essentially a soul ballad, its intensity mounting from a low boil early to emotive eruptions at the end. Buckley the singer knocks it out of the park, but Buckley the songwriter provided some juicy raw material.</p><p style=""box-sizing: border-box; margin-block: 24px 0px; max-width: 1248px; margin-left: auto !important; margin-right: auto !important; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.56; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 24px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;"" data-pasted=""true"">The song could have been just your typical lament from a lonely lover, but Buckley deepens the material by providing insight into the narrator&rsquo;s psyche and how it prevents him from the blissful reunion he seeks. &ldquo;Too young to hold on,&rdquo; he sings. &ldquo;And too old to just break free and run.&rdquo; That earthly purgatory between the two extremes is a place of endless torment, but it&rsquo;s presented here as a kind of rite of passage: &ldquo;Sometimes a man must awake to find, really/ He has no one.&rdquo;</p><p style=""box-sizing: border-box; margin-block: 24px 0px; max-width: 1248px; margin-left: auto !important; margin-right: auto !important; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.56; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 24px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;"">Once the narrator has established how he is complicit in his own agony, he can reveal just how deep it goes. Toward the end of the song, Buckley starts a series of lines with the phrase &ldquo;It&rsquo;s never over,&rdquo; with each successive line revealing just how bad he&rsquo;s got it. &ldquo;My kingdom for a kiss upon your shoulder,&rdquo; he sings, a twist on Richard III&rsquo;s request for a horse. Indeed he would give it all, his kingdom, his riches, even his blood, but he knows it won&rsquo;t be near enough: &ldquo;She is the tear that hangs within my soul forever.&rdquo;</p><p style=""box-sizing: border-box; margin-block: 24px 0px; max-width: 1248px; margin-left: auto !important; margin-right: auto !important; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.56; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 24px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;"">In the closing moments, Buckley pretty much leaves words behind, relying on a series of guttural moans and pain-wracked yelps to convey his feelings. Finally he leaves us with a sliver of hope for this fractured couple: &ldquo;Lover, you should&rsquo;ve come over/ &lsquo;Cause it&rsquo;s not too late.&rdquo; Jeff Buckley&rsquo;s haunting singing voice will never be forgotten, even considering the very short time it graced the world&rsquo;s stage. &ldquo;Lover, You Should&rsquo;ve Come Over&rdquo; proves how badly his songwriting is missed as well.</p>
