                            Content = @"
                            <p data-start=""161"" data-end=""487"" data-pasted=""true""><strong data-start=""161"" data-end=""177""><em data-start=""163"" data-end=""175"">Abbey Road</em></strong>, released in <strong data-start=""191"" data-end=""199"">1969</strong>, is one of <strong data-start=""211"" data-end=""227"">The Beatles&rsquo;</strong> most iconic and beloved albums &mdash; a masterpiece that marked the band&rsquo;s final recording sessions together. Though <em data-start=""340"" data-end=""351"">Let It Be</em> was released later, <em data-start=""372"" data-end=""384"">Abbey Road</em> was the <strong data-start=""393"" data-end=""445"">last album the group recorded as a complete unit</strong>, giving it a powerful sense of closure.</p><p data-start=""489"" data-end=""782"">The album was recorded at <strong data-start=""515"" data-end=""537"">Abbey Road Studios</strong> in London, which later became world-famous thanks to this release. Its <strong data-start=""609"" data-end=""634"">legendary cover photo</strong>&mdash;the four Beatles walking across the zebra crossing outside the studio&mdash;has become one of the most recognized and imitated images in music history.</p><p data-start=""784"" data-end=""1037"">Musically, <em data-start=""795"" data-end=""807"">Abbey Road</em> captures The Beatles at their most mature and experimental. It blends <strong data-start=""878"" data-end=""926"">rock, pop, blues, and progressive influences</strong>, showcasing their growth as composers and performers. The album features some of their most memorable songs:</p><ul data-start=""1038"" data-end=""1442""><li data-start=""1038"" data-end=""1126""><p data-start=""1040"" data-end=""1126""><strong data-start=""1040"" data-end=""1059"">&ldquo;Come Together&rdquo;</strong> &ndash; a dark, groovy opener driven by John Lennon&rsquo;s hypnotic vocals.</p></li><li data-start=""1127"" data-end=""1260""><p data-start=""1129"" data-end=""1260""><strong data-start=""1129"" data-e